<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06041237 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06041237 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SANTA-CLARA; COLLEGE; BASKETBALL; GAME; RESULT; CHART  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Santa Clara made a run at second place in the West Coast Conference onSaturday night, but the University of San Diego held off the Broncos 75-64.;   San Diego shot 61 percent from the field in the first half and the Broncoshad fallen behind 39-17 with 2 minutes, 13 seconds to go in the half beforehitting 13 straight unanswered points to narrow the gap to nine. Santa Claratrailed 41-30 at half.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  BRONCOS' RUSHES FALL SHORTSANTA CLARA USES THREE GUARDS TO APPLY PRESSUREON SAN DIEGO  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Saturday's Score: SAN DIEGO 75, SANTA CLARA 64. Highlight: A three-guardoffense and a pressure defense kept the Broncos in the game.Chart attached to the end of this article  </MEMO><TEXT>     Using a speedy three-guard lineup and a pressure defense that left centerRon Reis on the bench in the second half, the Broncos came back again with a13-1 run that closed the margin to 54-53 with 9:01 to play.;    But San Diego,which hit only 5 of 15 field goals in the second half, ended up with 28 freethrows thanks to the Broncos' battling to get the ball.;    Santa Clara CoachCarroll Williams said: &quot;We couldn't shoot the ball well early, just couldn'tget enough good shots. I thought our whole effort was very lackadaisical.;   &quot;However,&quot; he said, &quot;we played hard in some parts. It was really a valianteffort by some of our younger kids. I can't put my finger on any oneparticular thing, except for hustle.&quot;;    Santa Clara was led by Michael Woodsand LaCobe Phillips, who each scored 12 points, and Melvin Chinn, who chippedin 11.;    During the Broncos' second-half run, freshman DeWayne Lewis hadseven of the team's 13 points and it was his three-point basket that closedthe gap to 53-50. A three-pointer by Phillips made it 54-53 with 9:01 to play,but San Diego jumped back with nine straight points and that was theballgame.;    Santa Clara played without leading scorer Rhea Taylor, whosprained an ankle last Saturday against Gonzaga.;    The Broncos' recorddropped to 15-9, 6-4 in the WCC and left them in third place, one game aheadof Loyola Marymount. San Diego (16-7, 8-2) trails Pepperdine by one game.;SANTA CLARA (64);            fg-a  ft-a   tp;  Karich   1-4    0-0    2,; Velling  1-2    2-2    4,;  Reis     0-2    2-3    2,;  Chinn    5-15   1-2  11,;  Phillips 4-9    3-4   12,;  Schmitz  1-6    2-3    5,;  Stewart  1-3   1-3    3,;  Woods    5-8    1-2   12,;  Woolery  3-6    0-0    6,;  Lewis   3-5    0-0    7.;  Totals  24-60  12-19  64;  ...; SAN DIEGO (75);              fg-a  ft-a    tp;  Thomas      2-7    1-2     5,;  Woods       5-8    5-8   15,;  Bell        2-2    3-7     7 ,;  Brown       3-5    8-13   14,; Strickland  2-5    0-0     5,;  Probst      2-4    7-8    12,;  Watson     1-1    1-2     3,;  Holbert     3-7    0-0     9,;  Colvin      1-2    3-4    5.;  Totals     21-41  28-44   75.; ...; Santa Clara   3030 3434----6464; SanDiego     4141 3434----7575; ...;       Three-point goals -- Santa Clara 4-14(Woods 1-1, Lewis 1-3, Phillips 1-3, Schmitz 1-4, Woolery 0-1, Chinn 0-2), SanDiego 5-11 (Holbert 3-3, Strickland 1-2, Probst 1-3, Brown 0-3). Fouled out --Schmitz. Rebounds -- Santa Clara 30 (Chinn, Schmitz 5), San Diego 39 (Colvin12). Assists -- Santa Clara 12 (Phillips 3), San Diego 17 (Brown 5). Totalfouls -- Santa Clara 26, San Diego 18. A -- 2,500.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff and Wire Reports  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  San Diego  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910210  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  CHART  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  604  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday Fe